post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_8256293_8256293_2": {"length": 5, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 3286}, "so_8256293_8256369_2": {"length": 12, "quality": 0.9230769230769231, "section_id": 3286}, "so_8256293_8256293_1": {"length": 9, "quality": 0.75, "section_id": 3286}, "so_8256293_8256293_0": {"length": 4, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 3286}, "so_8256293_8256369_1": {"length": 4, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 3286}, "so_8256293_8256369_3": {"length": 5, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 3286}}, "n3337": {"so_8256293_8256293_2": {"length": 5, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 3156}, "so_8256293_8256369_2": {"length": 13, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 3156}, "so_8256293_8256293_1": {"length": 10, "quality": 0.8333333333333334, "section_id": 3156}, "so_8256293_8256293_0": {"length": 4, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 3156}, "so_8256293_8256369_1": {"length": 4, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 3156}, "so_8256293_8256369_3": {"length": 5, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 3156}}, "n4659": {"so_8256293_8256293_2": {"length": 5, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 4048}, "so_8256293_8256369_2": {"length": 9, "quality": 0.6923076923076923, "section_id": 4049}, "so_8256293_8256293_1": {"length": 7, "quality": 0.5833333333333334, "section_id": 384}, "so_8256293_8256369_3": {"length": 5, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 4048}}}, "8256369": {"Id": "8256369", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>From 8.5.9 of the 2003 standard:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_8256293_8256369_0\">If no initializer is specified for an object, and the object is of\n  (possibly cv-qualified) non-POD class type (or array thereof), the\n  object shall be default-initialized; if the object is of\n  const-qualified type, the underlying class type shall have a\n  user-declared default constructor. <strong>Otherwise, if no initializer is\n  specified for a nonstatic object, the object and its subobjects, if\n  any, have an indeterminate initial value</strong>); if the object or any of\n  its subobjects are of const-qualified type, the program is ill-formed.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The class you show is a POD, so the highlighted part applies, and your object will not be initialized at all (so section 8.5/5, which you quote, does not apply at all).</p>\n<p><strong>Edit:</strong> As per your comment, here the quote from section 8.5/5 of the final working draft of the current standard (I don't have the real standard, but the FDIS is supposedly very close):</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_8256293_8256369_1\">To default-initialize an object of type T means: </p>\n<p id=\"so_8256293_8256369_2\">\u2014 if T is a (possibly\n  cv-qualified) class type (Clause 9), the default constructor for T is\n  called (and the initialization is ill-formed if T has no accessible\n  default constructor); </p>\n<p id=\"so_8256293_8256369_3\">\u2014 if T is an array type, each element is\n  default-initialized; </p>\n<p id=\"so_8256293_8256369_4\">\u2014 <strong>otherwise, no initialization is performed.</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "160206", "LastActivityDate": "2011-11-24T20:27:05.430", "Score": "6", "CreationDate": "2011-11-24T11:35:06.893", "ParentId": "8256293", "CommentCount": "15", "OwnerUserId": "160206", "LastEditDate": "2011-11-24T20:27:05.430"}, "8257006": {"Id": "8257006", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Your variable is not initialized. \nUse </p>\n<pre><code>Int a = Int();\n</code></pre>\n<p>to initialize your POD or declare a standard constructor to make it non POD;\nBut you can also use your POD uninitialized for performance reasons like:</p>\n<pre><code>Int a;\na.i = 5;\n</code></pre>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2011-11-24T12:25:06.477", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2011-11-24T12:25:06.477", "ParentId": "8256293", "Score": "1", "OwnerUserId": "165958"}, "8256390": {"Id": "8256390", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>No, the object <code>a</code> is not default-initialized. If you want to default-initialize it, you have to say:</p>\n<pre><code>Int a = Int() ;\n</code></pre>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2011-11-24T11:37:09.513", "CommentCount": "3", "CreationDate": "2011-11-24T11:37:09.513", "ParentId": "8256293", "Score": "0", "OwnerUserId": "428857"}, "8256293": {"ViewCount": "3787", "Body": "<p>The C++ standard says (8.5/5):</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_8256293_8256293_0\">To default-initialize an object of type <code>T</code> means:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><p id=\"so_8256293_8256293_1\">If <code>T</code> is a non-POD class type (clause 9), the default constructor for <code>T</code> is called (and the initialization is ill-formed if <code>T</code> has no\n  accessible default constructor).</p></li>\n<li><p id=\"so_8256293_8256293_2\">If <code>T</code> is an array type, each element is default-initialized.</p></li>\n<li><p id=\"so_8256293_8256293_3\">Otherwise, the object is zero-initialized.</p></li>\n</ul>\n</blockquote>\n<p>With this code</p>\n<pre><code>struct Int { int i; };\n\nint main()\n{\n    Int a;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>the object <code>a</code> is default-initialized, but clearly <code>a.i</code> is not necessarily equal to 0 . Doesn't that contradict the standard, as <code>Int</code> is POD and is not an array ?</p>\n<p><strong>Edit</strong>  Changed from <code>class</code> to <code>struct</code> so that <code>Int</code> is a POD.</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "8256369", "Title": "Default initialization of POD vs. non-POD class types", "CreationDate": "2011-11-24T11:26:47.253", "Id": "8256293", "CommentCount": "3", "FavoriteCount": "0", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditDate": "2011-11-24T17:24:27.677", "LastEditorUserId": "34509", "LastActivityDate": "2011-11-24T20:27:05.430", "Score": "4", "OwnerUserId": "1042389", "Tags": "<c++><initialization><c++03>", "AnswerCount": "3"}});